Numbers Combination Algorithm
Find all possible combination of number to reach particular given sum

Hey guys how are you doing all?

Yesterday i was working on an algorithm can solve the combination problems.
Do you remember the Combination?

-If No, it's simply the answer of how many ways we can find X number(s) in a particular number?

For example assuming we're looking for how many ways we can get two number from the 5?

the law says: n c r = n! / (r! * n-c!)

so

n = 5
r = 2
c = 5-2 = 3

5! = 1 * 2 * 3 * 4 * 5 = 120
2! = 1 * 2 = 2
3! = 1 * 2 * 3 = 6

5! / (2! * 3!)
120 / (2 * 6)
120/12
____________
10

so we have 10 ways within the number 5 can give us two numbers

e.g 

Now we have the series of 5 numbers [3 , 5 , 4 , 9 , 7]

How many ways we can getting two numbers of this series?

A:
Way 01:     3 - 5
Way 02:     3 - 4
Way 03:     3 - 9
Way 04:     3 - 7
Way 05:     5 - 4
Way 06:     5 - 9
Way 07:     5 - 7
Way 08:     4 - 9
Way 09:     4 - 7
Way 10:     9 - 7

10 Ways.
__________

But what is the benefit of the combination or how can use it within a code? 

-For example lets assuming we have the following series of numeric values:

[50, 712, 578, 971, 3548, 964221.25, 7414]

The question is: 

What are the possible combination of numbers which can give us the value of 965904.25 after getting the summation?

Answer is: (712 + 971 + 964221.25) = 965904.25

You won't getting the above simple answer without the combination this is the way that can give you the correct answer of any equation result because it's assuming all perhaps equation can be applied inside this series.

Yesterday i made the algorithm in c# & i prefer to share it here for anyone potential.

Code:
================================================
/// <summary>
        /// Author: OmarNegm    
        /// This algorthim uses the combination in order to assuming all
        /// Perhaps summation operation using recursive method until getting the traget operation that
        /// Can give us the target summation value we're looking for
        /// e.g we looking for the summation process of 10 in the series[9, 5, 3 , 2]
        /// Answer: 5 + 3 + 2   
        ///  </summary>     
        /// <param name="doubleSeries">the series of all double values that we looking for the summation inside(50, 712.. etc)</param>
        /// <param name="targetValue">the target values of summation we looking for (4176)</param>
        /// <param name="currentNumber">this value will hold the last summation applied for each iteration. e.g the first arrange is 50 + 712 so the next recursive will hold the sum of (50+712) to be ready to be added to the upcoming values</param>
        /// <param name="currentIndex">if we start with the value 50 which is the first value so we have to compare it's summation with next element of the array. so the current index is [0] = 50 and the next index [1] = 712 so we will compare 50 + 712 etc..</param>
        /// <param name="latestSumSet">this string will keep the latest summation operation e.g now we're get the equation of 50+712. So this variable will keep the 50 + 712 as string. That will be your returned value</param>
        /// <param name="sorted">Checking if the array is already sorted in order to avoid the problems of negative number summation. 
        /// e.g if we're looking for 10 inside [11, 0, -1] the first key number which is the 11 will be greater than the 10 so the algorthim will not continue because of the break; line while we're looking for 11 + (-1) which is our correct result</param>
        /// <returns>string e.g  1 + 2 + 3 = 6</returns>
        public static string Combination(double[] doubleSeries, double targetValue, double currentNumber = 0,
            int currentIndex = -1, string latestSumSet = "", bool sorted = false)
        {
            if (!sorted)
            {

                //Performing Insertion Sort algorithm for sorting the elements of our series A-Z.
                for (int i = 0; i < doubleSeries.Length - 1; i++)
                {
                    int x = i + 1;
                    while (x > 0)
                    {
                        if (doubleSeries[x - 1] > doubleSeries[x])
                        {
                            double tempElement = doubleSeries[x - 1];
                            doubleSeries[x - 1] = doubleSeries[x];
                            doubleSeries[x] = tempElement;
                        }
                        x--;
                    }
                }
            }
            string lastSumOperation = "";
            for (int i = currentIndex + 1; i < doubleSeries.Length; i++)
            {
                //Collect the current values + the next element as string.
                string currentSumSet = (latestSumSet == "" ? "" : latestSumSet + " + ") + doubleSeries[i];
                //If the current result is grather than the target 
                //so no matter to continue adding the upcoming values
                if (currentNumber + doubleSeries[i] > targetValue) break;
                if ((currentNumber + doubleSeries[i]).Equals(targetValue))
                {
                    lastSumOperation = currentSumSet;
                    break;
                }
                else
                {
                    //Recurive and get a result of a new arranging
                    lastSumOperation = Combination(doubleSeries, targetValue,
                        currentNumber + doubleSeries[i], i, currentSumSet, true);
                    //Does we got it?
                    if (lastSumOperation != "")
                    {
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
            return lastSumOperation;
        }

